    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="118"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d118">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857/320</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Cork</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Frost</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cork</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Queenstown</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1917-02-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 8, 12.30
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Provisional British Furness Withy S. S. <hi rend="italic">Turino</hi> of London
                    cleared Newport News January 19, general cargo, mounted 4–inch gun visible on
                    stern, ship complement 36. When about 80 miles southwest Fastnet was torpedoed
                    without any warning, 2.45 p.m. Explosion killed chief engineer and three negro
                    firemen, of whom one named <persName corresp="#p_WHL1">Washington</persName>
                    seems to have had some claims to American citizenship.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d118fn1">According to telegrams of Feb. 8 and 9, he was of Canadian
                        citizenship.</note> Submarine showed all possible consideration after
                    explosion, excusing absence of warning by fear of <hi rend="italic"
                        >Turino’s</hi> gun; placed survivors on Italian S. S. <hi rend="italic"
                        >Famiglia</hi> which submarine used as tender. All survivors except three,
                    who were kept as stokers, were taken off at 4 p.m., February 6, and now landed
                    Queenstown by unarmed admiralty tug, 29 in all; one native American, Calvin Bay
                    of Fillmore, <pb facs="0295" n="123" xml:id="pg_123"/> Utah. Am taking
                    affidavits. Have cabled Department and telegraphed Ambassador, Consul
                    General.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Frost</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
